Vladimir Poutine and the Risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – Russia's invasion of Ukraine on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war with the potential to destroy our civilization.
This invasion was preceded by a lengthy meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the start of Chinese New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
At the end of this meeting, the two men published a 5,000-word document, carefully drafted, announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given Putin a free hand to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and consider his confirmation as a life president of China later in the year a mere formality.
After consolidating all powers in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario according to which he will be elevated to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After getting Xi's support, Putin has embarked on realizing the dream of his life with incredible brutality.
Approaching his 70s, Putin believes that if he wants to leave his mark on Russian history, it is now or never.
But his conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems he believes that the Russian people need a tsar to follow blindly.
This is precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it's a vision that distorts "the soul" of Russia, emotional to the point of sentimentality.
As a child, I met many Russian soldiers when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned that they were ready to share their last piece of bread with you if you asked them.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I created a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the disintegration of the Soviet empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, the disintegration had already begun.
I created a foundation in Russia, then I did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner authorized to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989 just before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I don't know Putin personally, but I have observed his rise to power very closely, being aware of his cruelty.
He reduced the capital of Chechnya, Grozny, to ruins. And he threatens to do the same with the Ukrainian capital, Kyiv.
Putin was once a cunning operator of the KGB, but it seems he has changed recently.
Having developed a fixed idea, it seems he has lost touch with reality.
He has certainly miscalculated the situation in Ukraine.
He expected the Russian-speaking Ukrainians to welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but they turned out to be in exactly the same position as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have set up an incredibly courageous resistance against an opponent that nothing seems able to stop.
In July 2021, Putin published a long essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are really one people and that Ukrainians have been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was originally the seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
Mais dans la deuxième partie, c'est Poutine qui a été induit en erreur.
Il aurait dû se montrer plus prudent.
De nombreux Ukrainiens ont combattu vaillamment lors des manifestations 'Euromaidan en 2014.
Les événements de 2014 l'ont plongé dans une colère noire.
Mais l'armée russe a fait piètre figure lorsqu'elle a reçu l'ordre d'attaquer ses frères ukrainiens.
The entrenched corruption in defense contract assignments has also played an important role in its inadequate results.
However, rather than take blame for this, Putin seems to have literally lost his mind.
He has decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and seems to act without encountering any resistance.
He launches the entire Russian army into battle and disregards all rules of war, including indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals have been hit and the electrical network that supplies the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In Mariupol under siege, 400,000 people have been without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia could well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to purchase Russian-made MiG fighter jets, which Ukrainian pilots know how to fly.
This could make all the difference.
No matter the outcome, Putin has already done wonders by strengthening the determination and unity of the EU.
Pendant ce temps, Xi似乎已经意识到普京在单打独斗。
3月8日，一天前中国外交部长王毅坚持认为中俄友谊要“牢固”，习近平分别致电法国总统埃马纽埃尔·马克龙和德国总理奥拉夫·朔尔茨表示支持他们的和平恢复努力。
他希望尽可能表现出克制以避免人道危机。
普京是否听从习近平的意愿还远未确定。
我们只能希望普京和习近平在摧毁我们的文明之前被罢免。
